---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Research" description="Gavin Robert Foster's research on social cognition, theory of mind, norm psychology, and Kantian philosophy.">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-label">Research</p>
      <h1>Research Program</h1>
      <p class="page-intro">
        My work spans philosophy of mind and cognitive science, comparative and developmental
        psychology, epistemology, and Kant's theoretical and moral philosophy. I pursue these
        questions both empirically (through hands-on work in comparative psychology) and
        philosophically, through careful conceptual and textual analysis.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container page-body">

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Theory of Mind &amp; Mindreading</h2>
      <p>
        A central thread of my research concerns how minds represent other minds. I work on the
        attribution of knowledge, belief, and desire across species, including the <em>logical
        problem of mindreading</em>, the question of whether non-human animals genuinely attribute
        mental states, and factive accounts of knowledge attribution in monkeys and great apes.
      </p>
      <p>
        My MA thesis developed a "multiple soft-indicators" model designed to dissolve the logical
        problem, and my recent work with Evan Westra examines the role of metarepresentation in
        desire-attribution. This research also bears on the status of folk psychology itself: I argue
        that evidence from animal and infant mindreading poses serious empirical challenges for
        fictionalist and interpretivist accounts of the mental.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Comparative &amp; Developmental Cognition</h2>
      <p>
        I combine philosophical analysis with empirical research on animal minds. As a visiting
        scholar in Christopher Krupenye's Social and Cognitive Origins Group at Johns Hopkins,
        I helped launch a canine cognition lab and design theory-of-mind experiments with dogs,
        including published work on whether dogs rationally infer the causes of failed actions.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am interested in what comparative and developmental evidence, from monkeys and great apes
        to dogs and human infants, can tell us about the structure and origins of social cognition.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Norm Psychology</h2>
      <p>
        I study the cognitive and evolutionary foundations of social norms: what it takes for a
        creature to genuinely possess and be governed by norms, and how norms are acquired, maintained,
        and enforced, including in childhood. A recurring question is whether non-human animals, and
        primates in particular, count as normative creatures, and what the right evidence for
        normativity would be.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Bounded Rationality</h2>
      <p>
        I work on norms of rationality for real, cognitively finite agents, and on what a non-ideal
        epistemology should look like. This research is Kantian in spirit, extending Kantian ideas
        about autonomy and the proper use of reason into the philosophy of inquiry, with attention to
        how bounded agents ought to manage attention, rely on heuristics, and decide when to stop
        inquiring.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Kant on Moral Psychology &amp; Education</h2>
      <p>
        My historical work focuses on Kant's moral psychology and philosophy of education, especially
        his account of how human beings develop from infancy into autonomous moral agents. I read these
        texts in dialogue with contemporary developmental and moral psychology, asking how Kant's
        framework can be squared with our best empirical understanding of moral development.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="research-block">
      <h2>Funded Projects</h2>
      <div class="card-list">
        <div class="card">
          <p class="card-meta">SSHRC CGS-D · 2024–2028</p>
          <p class="card-title">Middle-Ground Conceptualism, Non-Human Animals, and Persistent Challenges in Comparative Psychology</p>
          <p class="card-desc">A four-year doctoral project on conceptualism and the interpretation of animal cognition.</p>
          <div class="card-tags">
            <span class="tag">Animal Minds</span>
            <span class="tag">Conceptualism</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <p class="card-meta">PROMISE Grant · Purdue · 2026</p>
          <p class="card-title">Animal Minds: New Theories and New Observations</p>
          <p class="card-desc">Bridging new theoretical work on animal cognition with fresh empirical observation.</p>
          <div class="card-tags">
            <span class="tag">Comparative Cognition</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <p class="card-meta">PROMISE Grant · Purdue · 2024</p>
          <p class="card-title">Triadic Approaches in Philosophy of Science</p>
          <p class="card-desc">Revealing the "gloss" of mental representations without succumbing to fictionalism.</p>
          <div class="card-tags">
            <span class="tag">Philosophy of Science</span>
            <span class="tag">Fictionalism</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <p class="card-meta">SSHRC CGS-M · 2023</p>
          <p class="card-title">The Emergence of Thought: Continual or All-at-Once</p>
          <p class="card-desc">A master's project on the developmental and evolutionary emergence of conceptual thought.</p>
          <div class="card-tags">
            <span class="tag">Concepts</span>
            <span class="tag">Development</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</Layout>

